TRAPPING RAIN WATER - LeetCode Hard (Java Solution)
=====================================================

PROBLEM UNDERSTANDING
----------------------
Given an array `height` where each element represents the height of a bar
in a histogram (width 1 each), compute how much water gets trapped between
the bars after it rains.

APPROACH
--------
For any index i, the water trapped above it equals:
    min(maxLeft, maxRight) - height[i]

where maxLeft is the tallest bar to its left (including itself) and maxRight
is the tallest bar to its right (including itself). The naive approach
computes these two arrays separately (O(n) space). We can do better with
a TWO POINTERS technique: maintain `left` and `right` pointers along with
`leftMax` and `rightMax`. Whichever side has the smaller max is guaranteed
to trap water based on that max, because the other side has at least that
much height blocking it - so we can resolve one side at a time without
knowing the full arrays.

ALGORITHM
---------
1. Initialize left = 0, right = n - 1, leftMax = 0, rightMax = 0, water = 0.
2. While left < right:
   - If height[left] < height[right]:
       - If height[left] >= leftMax, update leftMax = height[left].
       - Else, add (leftMax - height[left]) to water.
       - Move left forward.
   - Else:
       - If height[right] >= rightMax, update rightMax = height[right].
       - Else, add (rightMax - height[right]) to water.
       - Move right backward.
3. Return water.

CODE (JAVA)
-----------
class Solution {
    public int trap(int[] height) {
        if (height == null || height.length == 0) return 0;

        int left = 0, right = height.length - 1;
        int leftMax = 0, rightMax = 0;
        int water = 0;

        while (left < right) {
            if (height[left] < height[right]) {
                if (height[left] >= leftMax) {
                    leftMax = height[left];
                } else {
                    water += leftMax - height[left];
                }
                left++;
            } else {
                if (height[right] >= rightMax) {
                    rightMax = height[right];
                } else {
                    water += rightMax - height[right];
                }
                right--;
            }
        }

        return water;
    }
}

LINE-BY-LINE EXPLANATION
-------------------------
- if (height == null || height.length == 0) return 0;
    Handles empty/null input safely.
- int left = 0, right = height.length - 1;
    Two pointers starting from both ends.
- int leftMax = 0, rightMax = 0;
    Tracks the tallest bar seen so far from each side.
- int water = 0;
    Accumulates total trapped water.
- while (left < right)
    Continue until the pointers meet.
- if (height[left] < height[right])
    The side with the smaller current bar is the one we process - its
    bound is safely determined by leftMax, since rightMax must be at
    least height[right] > height[left].
- if (height[left] >= leftMax) leftMax = height[left];
    Current bar is a new tallest wall on the left, so it traps nothing itself.
- else water += leftMax - height[left];
    Otherwise, this bar is shorter than the tallest wall behind it, so it
    traps (leftMax - height[left]) water.
- left++;
    Move inward.
- The else branch mirrors this logic symmetrically for the right pointer.
- return water;
    Final trapped water total.

DRY RUN
-------
Input: height = [0,1,0,2,1,0,1,3,2,1,2,1]

left | right | height[left] | height[right] | leftMax | rightMax | water | Action
-----|-------|--------------|---------------|---------|----------|-------|--------
0    | 11    | 0            | 1             | 0       | 0        | 0     | height[left]>=leftMax, leftMax stays 0, left++
1    | 11    | 1            | 1             | 1       | 0        | 0     | height[left]>=leftMax, leftMax=1, left++
2    | 11    | 0            | 1             | 1       | 0        | 1     | height[left]<leftMax, water += 1-0=1 -> water=1, left++
3    | 11    | 2            | 1             | 1       | 0        | 1     | height[left]>=height[right], process right: rightMax=1, right--
3    | 10    | 2            | 2             | 1       | 1        | 1     | height[left]>=height[right], process right: rightMax=2, right--
...  | ...   | ...          | ...           | ...     | ...      | ...   | continues similarly

Final result: water = 6, matching the expected output for this classic example.

COMPLEXITY
----------
- Time:  O(n)  - each pointer moves at most n times total, single pass.
- Space: O(1)  - only a few integer variables used, no extra arrays.

EDGE CASES
----------
- Empty array (height.length == 0): returns 0 immediately.
- All bars same height: no water trapped, since no bar exceeds the height
  of a neighbor.
- Strictly increasing or decreasing array: no water trapped (no basin exists).
- Single element or two elements: loop doesn't execute (left < right fails
  or immediately equal), returns 0.
- Large input (up to 2 * 10^4 per constraints): O(n) time/space keeps this
  efficient.
